<font color="#FF0000">THE SIREN'S SONG</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 13  0:26:49 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Sometimes, late at night I get on line, read, and react, and shudder to think what I did the following morning when clarity has returned. Sometimes, in the coffee mornings I don't even recognize what I wrote the night before.  Call it PTSD (perhaps - due to 25 years of hearing too much (?)), Call it the Shrink's Syndrome, call it control, or just overwhelmed. Call it just being human. <br><br>
Sometimes I feel like Ulysses, lashed to the mast as the sirens sing, songs of madness, songs of rapture, songs of &quot;one step over the line, sweet Jesus, one step over the line&quot; (thanks - Brewer and Shipley, 1967) , and I need those ropes that lash me to the mast, that hold my course, midst the horrors of what I hear, and see, to not let go of me. <br><br>
Yes, this is the Crazy Corner, for all including ME. To vent and to let go, to yell and howl at the moon, to scream at the wife, to yell at the kids, to pound pointless plunder on the keyboard. Yes, even me, crazy as a fool too, sometimes, so don't hold me to standards I can't possible meet.<br><br>
DocDel, Tom, Betty, Tanker, Chet, there but for the grace of college go I.<br><br>
Sometimes I just want to tell you all, survivors of horror, that I too, have heard the sirens song that you have experienced, in my own way,  the call of madness, the screaming voice of violence, the pain.  Nothing more, nothing less. I mean no disrespect, ever, and if any has been taken, I offer sincere apologies.<br><br>
Doc Spatz
